  "opinion": "As a 19-year-old full-time student in New York, I’ve seen firsthand how stereotype threat affects students in STEM fields. Stereotype threat isn’t just a theoretical concept—it’s a real, emotional weight that lingers when someone feels their identity might be judged negatively by society. For me, growing up in a household where my mother only finished lower secondary school and my father completed upper secondary, I’ve experienced the tension of being a student who’s aware of how my background might influence my academic path. When I take math or physics tests, I often wonder if my parents’ educational limitations will make me seem 'less capable' in these subjects. This fear isn’t just about grades—it’s about self-doubt that can hold me back from fully engaging with the material. Stereotype threat in STEM is particularly damaging because it’s rooted in the idea that certain groups—like women or people from lower-income backgrounds—are less suited for technical fields. But as someone who’s curious and active in volunteering at local science fairs, I’ve seen how addressing this issue can make a real difference. We need to normalize conversations about bias in classrooms, provide mentorship programs that connect students with role models who look like them, and create inclusive environments where everyone feels their worth isn’t tied to their gender or background. It’s not just about fixing the problem—it’s about building confidence so students can thrive without feeling like they’re failing because of who they are.",
